  "prompt": "In genetics, what is an example of a monohybrid cross offspring?",
  "response": "In a monohybrid cross, an offspring results from parents with different alleles for a single trait. A classic example is Mendel's pea plant experiments with flower color.\n\nLet's say pure-breeding purple-flowered plants (PP) are crossed with pure-breeding white-flowered plants (pp):\n\n\u2022 Parents: PP (purple) x pp (white)\n\u2022 First generation (F1) offspring: All Pp (purple, showing dominant trait)\n\nIn this case, the F1 generation offspring would all have purple flowers, even though they carry both purple (dominant) and white (recessive) alleles. This demonstrates how dominant and recessive alleles interact in a monohybrid cross.\n\nA punnet square would show:\nP p\nP Pp Pp\np Pp Pp\n\nThe offspring are all heterozygous (Pp) and phenotypically purple, illustrating a fundamental principle of Mendelian inheritance.",
